    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `The scenario represents a case of angioedema manifested as tongue swelling with no other symptoms pointing towards allergy or anaphylaxis. Angioedema is localized deep dermis, subcutaneous, or submucosal swelling resulting from extravasation of fluid into interstitial tissue (blood vessel leakage). It can occur in isolation, accompanied by urticaria, or as a component of anaphylaxis. Angioedema typically affects gravity-independent areas with loose connective tissue such as face, lips, tongues, throat, uvula, larynx, extremities and genitalia. Bradykinin-induced angioedema is not associated with other manifestations of allergic reaction such as urticaria, respiratory and/or circulatory symptoms, or pruritus. There is a more prolonged time course with signs and symptoms usually developing over 24-36 hours and resolving within 2 to 4 days. Angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors (ACEIs) such as captopril, ramipril, lisinopril, enalapril, and perindopril are the most common triggering factors for bradykinin-induced angioedema; therefore, the most likely cause to this presentation would be the ACEI ramipril. Although anaphylaxis can have angioedema as a manifestation, the absences of urticaria, circulatory/respiratory symptoms and pruritus makes this diagnosis remote. Acquired C1esterase inhibitor (C1-INH) deficiency, also called acquired angioedema (AAE), is a rare syndrome presenting with recurrent episodes of angioedema without urticaria. This syndrome is sometimes associated with B cell lymphoproliferative disorders. Like ACEI-induced angioedema, manifestations include swelling of the face, tongue, upper respiratory tract, or bowel walls. C1-INH deficiency presents similar to hereditary angioedema (HAA); however, unlike patients with HAA who are often young, patients with this disease are often older than 40 years. Although C1-INH deficiency can be a diagnosis in this man, its rarity makes it a less likely possibility. Statins such as atorvastatin and metformin are not associated with angioedema, especially the bradykinin-induced type.`,
