    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Adenosine is the treatment of choice for narrow-complex supraventricular tachycardias (SVTs). The mechanism of action is by transient blockage of impulse transmission through the AV node. It has no or little effect on myocytes or other parts of the cardiac conductive system. The half-life is short and 10-15 seconds (not minutes). Adenosine is given as bolus, followed by saline flush. It efficiently reduces the heart rate and improves cardiac output once the heart rate slowed down. Contraindications to adenosine administration include: second- or third-degree AV block (except patients with a functioning artificial pacemaker), sinus node disease such as sick sinus syndrome or symptomatic sinus bradycardia (except in patients with a functioning artificial pacemaker), known or suspected bronchoconstructive or bronchospastic disease such as asthma or COPD, and known hypersensitivity to adenosine.`,
