    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `There are 4 benign ECG changes associated with therapeutic levels of digoxin, including: (1) T-wave changes such as flattening or inversion; (2) QT interval shortening (not prolongation); (3) "Scooped" appearance of ST segment with ST segment depression; (4) Increased amplitude of U-wave. ECG changes in toxic levels of digoxin include: Frequent PVCs, especially in a sick heart – the most common arrhythmia; Supraventricular tachyarrhythmias; AV block (including PR interval lengthening in 1st degree AV block); Junctional escape rhythms; Prolongation of PR interval; Bidirectional ventricular tachycardia with an alternating axis of the QRS complex is rare but the most specific ECG finding of digoxin toxicity. Prolongation of QT interval is not an ECG feature of digoxin use or toxicity.`,
